[[sn:Wamyō Ruijushō]] [[en:Wamyō Ruijushō]]
[[Category:Pages without translation templates]] <!--enwiki derived wikidata interwikis--> {{Commons category|Wamyō ruijushō}} [[de:Wamyō ruijushō]] [[fa:وامیو رویجوشو]] [[fr:Wamyō ruijushō]] [[it:Wamyō ruijushō]] [[ja:和名類聚抄]] [[ko:화명류취초]] [[ru:Вамё Руйдзюсё]] [[uk:Вамьо Руйдзюсьо]] [[zh:和名類聚抄]]

{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q2702542]] Wikidata name: Wamyō Ruijushō [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 10:21, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} {{Short description|Japanese dictionary of Chinese characters}} {{ref-improve|date=February 2016}} {{italic title}} [[File:Вамё Руйдзюсё.jpg|thumb]] The {{nihongo|'''''Wamyō ruijushō''''' or '''''Wamyō ruijūshō'''''|和名類聚抄||"Japanese names [for things], classified and annotated"}} is a 938 CE [[:en:Japanese dictionary|Japanese dictionary]] of [[:en:Chinese characters|Chinese characters]]. The [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]] scholar [[:en:Minamoto no Shitagō|Minamoto no Shitagō]] (源順, 911–983 CE) began compilation in 934, at the request of [[:en:Emperor Daigo|Emperor Daigo]]'s daughter. This ''Wamyō ruijushō'' title is abbreviated as ''Wamyōshō'', and has graphic variants of 和名類聚抄 with ''wa'' [[Wikt:和|和]] "harmony; Japan" for ''[[:en:Wa (Japan)|wa]]'' [[Wikt:倭|倭]] "dwarf; Japan" and 倭名類聚鈔 with ''shō'' [[Wikt:鈔|鈔]] "copy; summarize" for ''shō'' [[Wikt:抄|抄]] "copy; annotate".
The ''Wamyō ruijushō'' is the oldest extant Japanese dictionary organized into semantic headings, analogous to a Western language [[:en:thesaurus|thesaurus]]. This ancient [[:en:lexicographical|lexicographical]] [[:en:Collation|Collation]] system was developed in [[:en:Chinese dictionaries|Chinese dictionaries]] like the ''[[:en:Erya|Erya]]'', ''[[:en:Xiao Erya|Xiao Erya]]'', and ''[[:en:Shiming|Shiming]]''. The ''Wamyōshō'' categorizes ''[[:en:Kanji|Kanji]]'' vocabulary, primarily [[:en:nouns|nouns]], into main headings (''bu'' [[Wikt:部|部]]) divided into subheadings (''rui'' [[Wikt:類|類]]). For instance, the ''tenchi'' (天地 "heaven and earth") heading includes eight semantic divisions like ''seishuku'' (星宿 "stars and constellations"), ''un'u'' (雲雨 "clouds and rain"), and ''fūsetsu'' (風雪 "wind and snow").
Each dictionary entry gives the Chinese character, sources cited, [[:en:Chinese pronunciation|Chinese pronunciation]]s (with either a [[:en:homonym|homonym]] or ''[[:en:fanqie|fanqie]]'' spelling), definitions, and corresponding Japanese readings (in the ancient ''[[:en:Man&#39;yōgana|Man&#39;yōgana]]'' system using kanji to represent Japanese pronunciation). It cites over 290 sources, both Chinese (for example, the ''[[:en:Shuowen Jiezi|Shuowen Jiezi]]'') and Japanese (the ''[[:en:Man'yōshū|Man'yōshū]]'').
The ''Wamyō ruijushō'', survives in both a 10-volume edition (十巻本) and a 20-volume edition (二十巻本). The larger one was published in 1617 with a commentary by [[Nawa Dōen]] (那波道円, 1595–1648) and was used in the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]] until the 1883 publication of the 10-volume edition annotated by [[Kariya Ekisai]] (狩谷棭齋, 1775–1835),{{r|OxfordRef_Ekisai}} also known as the ''Senchū Wamyō ruijushō'' (箋注倭名類聚抄 "Annotated commentary to the ''Wamyō ruijushō''"). The 10-volume edition has 24 main headings divided into a total of 128 subheadings, while the 20-volume version has 32 and 249, respectively. The table below illustrates how words are semantically categorized in the 10-volume edition.
